# 5. Governing Physical Principles

Instead of enforcing full Navier-Stokes equations, the following aerodynamic constraints are incorporated.

---

## 5.1 Lift–Pressure Consistency

According to aerodynamic theory, lift is generated by the pressure difference between the upper and lower airfoil surfaces.

Lift coefficient can be approximated as:

Cl ∝ ∫ Cp dx

This implies that the predicted pressure distribution should be consistent with the predicted lift coefficient.

### Constraint

Lift computed from predicted Cp should agree with predicted Cl.

---

## 5.2 Pressure Smoothness

Pressure distributions around aerodynamic surfaces are generally smooth except near sharp flow transitions.

Physically realistic Cp curves should not contain high-frequency oscillations.

### Constraint

Penalize rapid variation between neighboring Cp points.

Mathematically:

Smoothness ∝ Σ(Cp(i+1) − Cp(i))²

This acts as a regularization term encouraging realistic pressure fields.

---

## 5.3 Positive Drag Constraint

Aerodynamic drag cannot be negative under normal operating conditions.

### Constraint

Cd ≥ 0

Any prediction violating this condition receives a penalty.

---

## 5.4 Pressure Drag Consistency

The dataset includes both:

- Total drag coefficient (Cd)
- Pressure drag coefficient (Cdp)

Physical drag decomposition requires:

Cd ≥ Cdp

since total drag includes pressure drag plus skin-friction contributions.

### Constraint

Predictions violating this inequality are penalized.

---

# 6. Data Loss Formulation

The standard supervised learning objective is retained.

For a batch of predictions:

Data Loss:

L_data = MSE(Cl) + MSE(Cd) + MSE(Cp)

This ensures agreement with measured aerodynamic quantities.

---

# 7. Physics Loss Terms

## 7.1 Lift Consistency Loss

A surrogate lift value is estimated from the predicted pressure distribution.

Physics loss:

L_lift = MSE(Cl_pred, Cl_from_Cp)

Purpose:

Enforces consistency between force coefficients and pressure fields.

---

## 7.2 Pressure Smoothness Loss

L_smooth = Mean[(Cp(i+1) − Cp(i))²]

Purpose:

Suppresses non-physical oscillations in predicted pressure distributions.

---

## 7.3 Drag Positivity Loss

L_drag = ReLU(−Cd)

Purpose:

Ensures non-negative drag predictions.

---

## 7.4 Drag Consistency Loss

L_cdp = ReLU(Cdp − Cd)

Purpose:

Ensures total drag remains greater than or equal to pressure drag.

---

# 8. Total PINN Objective Function

The final optimization objective combines data fidelity and physics constraints.

L_total = L_data + λ₁L_lift + λ₂L_smooth + λ₃L_drag + λ₄L_cdp

where:

| Parameter | Description |
|------------|-------------|
| λ₁ | Lift consistency weight |
| λ₂ | Pressure smoothness weight |
| λ₃ | Drag positivity weight |
| λ₄ | Drag consistency weight |

Initial values:

| Weight | Value |
|----------|----------|
| λ₁ | 1.0 |
| λ₂ | 0.01 |
| λ₃ | 0.1 |
| λ₄ | 0.1 |

These values will be tuned experimentally during subsequent training stages.

