# 12. Conclusion

A Physics-Informed Aerodynamic Surrogate PINN was formulated for the NASA Airfoil Learning Dataset. Because the dataset does not contain full CFD flow-field information, the proposed framework incorporates aerodynamic knowledge through pressure-force consistency, pressure smoothness constraints, and drag-related physical constraints.

The resulting objective function combines traditional supervised learning with domain-specific physics losses, providing a foundation for the next phase of the project: PINN implementation, training, and comparison against the baseline MLP and Fourier Neural Operator (FNO) models.

This formulation establishes the first physics-informed benchmark within the aerodynamic surrogate modeling pipeline and serves as the basis for all subsequent PINN experiments.
